@ijuma I think the way this is built up is partly historical, partly convenience. There used to only be the one project, so everything was simple and we could use the standardized `kafka-run-class`. I think it continued to be used as we added more subprojects and just continued to accumulate code and CLASSPATHs to handle different projects. `kafka-run-class` does enough useful stuff that it'd be painful to maintain separate copies of it as they will diverge, we'd need to be very vigilant about applying fixes across all of them, etc.

I think the best solution is probably to refactor the scripts so we can pull CLASSPATH setup to parent scripts, and in the few cases where it makes sense (e.g. the dozens of tools scripts), provide wrapper helper scripts, e.g. `kafka-tools-run-class` which is a small wrapper around `kafka-run-class` and allows us to keep all the tool-specific scripts simple.

Wrt dependencies, I think this is also due to the way we currently collect dependent libs. I'm honestly not sure how to do this better with gradle, but we need to sort out shared dependencies and be able to filter transitive dependencies that are already available elsewhere via the classpath.
